{{refimprove|date=April 2014}} The '''National Socialist Teachers League''' ([[German language|German]]: {{lang|de|'''Nationalsozialistische Lehrerbund'''}}, '''NSLB'''), was established on 21 April 1929.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pine |first=L. |title=Education in Nazi Germany |location=Oxford |publisher=Berg |year=2010 |pages=14}}</ref> Its original name was the Organization of National Socialist Educators.<ref>[[Christian Zentner]] and [[Friedemann Bedürftig]] ''[[The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich]]'' New York: Macmillan 1991 p.435</ref> Its founder and first leader was former schoolteacher and [[Bayreuth]] [[Gauleiter]] [[Hans Schemm]].<ref>[[Christian Zentner]] and [[Friedemann Bedürftig]] ''[[The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich]]'' New York: Macmillan 1991 p.834</ref> The organization was based in Bayreuth at the [[House of German Education]]. On October 27, 1938 the NSLB opened its own [[Realschule]] for teacher training in Bayreuth.<ref>[[Christian Zentner]] and [[Friedemann Bedürftig]] ''[[The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich]]'' New York: Macmillan 1991 pp.435-6</ref>
After Schemm's death in 1935, the new leader, or ''Reichswalter'', was [[Fritz Wächtler]].<ref>[[Christian Zentner]] and [[Friedemann Bedürftig]] ''[[The Encyclopedia of the Third Reich]]'' New York: Macmillan 1991 pp.435-6</ref>
This organization saw itself as "the common effort of all persons who saw themselves as teachers or wanted to be seen as educators, independently from background or education and from the type of educational institution". Its goal was to make the [[Nazism|National Socialist]] worldview and foundation of all education and especially of schooling. In order to achieve this it sought to have an effect on the political viewpoint of educators, insisting on the further development of their spirit along Nationalsocialist lines. Organized mountain excursions in places called {{lang|de|Reichsaustauschlager}} (Exchange Camps of the Reich) were perceived as helping in this purpose.
The organization was dissolved in 1943 by the financial administration of the NSDAP.<ref>[https://www.historisches-lexikon-bayerns.de/Lexikon/Nationalsozialistischer_Lehrerbund_(NSLB),_1929-1943#Bedeutungsverlust_und_Aufl.C3.B6sung Bedeutungsverlust und Auflösung]</ref>
