'''Nikolay Nikolayevich Konstantinov'''  ({{lang-ru|Николай Николаевич Константинов}}; born 2 January 1932) is a leading [[USSR|Soviet]] and [[Russia]]n [[mathematical education|mathematical educator]] and organizer of numerous [[mathematics competitions]] for [[high school student]]s.  He is best known as the creator and chief organizer of the [[Tournament of the Towns]].<ref>[http://www.amt.edu.au/imtot.html International Mathematics Tournament of Towns]</ref>  For his work he was awarded the [[Paul Erdős]] award in 1992.<ref>[http://www.amt.edu.au/wfnmcaw.html David Hilbert and Paul Erdös Awards]</ref>

== Biography ==
Konstantinov was born and grew up in [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]].  He graduated from the [[MSU Faculty of Physics|Physics Department]] of the [[Lomonosov Moscow State University|Moscow State University]] in 1954, and later received a [[Ph.D.]] in [[physics]].

In the 1950s he started  a [[math circle]] in Moscow University and since the 1960s in a number of Moscow high schools.  He continued working with schools developing special classes with mathematics concentration and individual approach to learning.  His students went on to win mathematics competitions on all levels and dozens of them became well known mathematicians.

In 1978, Konstantinov started the [[Mikhail Lomonosov|Lomonosov]] tournament, a multi-subject science competition.  This tournament is continued every year since then.  In 1980, he started the international [[Tournament of the Towns]] which is now organized in over 150 towns in 25 countries.<ref>"[http://www.amt.canberra.edu.au/mc19912.html Birth of the Tournament of the Towns]", an article by N.N. Konstantinov, J.B. Tabov and P.J. Taylor in ''Mathematics Competitions'', Vol. 4, No. 2, 1991, pp. 28-41.</ref><ref>[http://www.svoboda.org/programs/edu/2004/edu.060204.asp Mathematics competitions] (in [[Russian language|Russian]]), a [[Radio Liberty]] interview with Nikolay Konstantinov.</ref>

In 1990 Konstantinov was one of the founders of [[Independent University of Moscow]], one of the leading institutions of higher learning in mathematics in Russia.<ref>"[http://shkolazhizni.ru/archive/0/n-15786/ Why Konstantinov is a legend]" (in [[Russian language|Russian]]), an article in ''Shkola Zhizni'' magazine, 25 May 2008.</ref>

Even now, in his late 80's, Konstantinov continues working in Moscow High School 179 and is an editor of [[Kvant magazine]], a popular Russian science publication.

