'''Positive handling''' is a term used in [[United Kingdom|British]] primary and [[Special education|special-needs education]] for [[physical restraint]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reid|first1=Ken|last2=Morgan|first2=Nicola S.|title=Tackling Behaviour in Your Primary School: A Practical Handbook for Teachers|date=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415670234|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=neEGycAflMYC&lpg=PA46&dq=%22positive%20handling%22&pg=PA46#v=onepage&q=%22positive%20handling%22&f=false|quote=In fact restraint is often referred to by professionals as "positive handling"}}</ref> It has been described as "risk-reduced physical interventions that form part of the [[Holism|holistic]] response"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hayden|first1=Carol|title=Children in Trouble: The Role of Families, Schools and Communities|date=2007|isbn=9780230207998|page=94|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m5gcBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA94&dq=%22positive%20handling%22&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q=%22positive%20handling%22&f=false|accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref> The term has been in use since at least 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Jacqui|title=Hansard: Written answers|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199900/cmhansrd/vo000725/text/00725w19.htm|publisher=House of Commons|accessdate=29 March 2016|date=25 July 2000|quote=To improve the education for children with emotional and behavioural difficulties in particular, this year we have:... consulted on additional guidance on promoting positive handling strategies for pupils with severe behavioural difficulties.}}</ref>

Positive handling refers to a graduated approach that moves towards the control of extreme [[Behavior|behaviour]] by adopting the least intrusive intervention for the shortest period of time to achieve the aim. It is one of the most efficient method of training on how to control a disruptive pupil whilst protecting them, and remaining compliant with legislation.

The objective of prevention and intervention techniques is to prevent [[school violence]] from occurring. Support for staff is the key to handling student aggression in schools.

To support it, the staff requires [[training]], which is also a legal obligation of teaching institutions.The avoidance of any physical intervention is a first priority. The principle involves the graduated use of [[de-escalation]] approaches before resorting to physical intervention as the last resort, if any other approaches have failed or are likely to fail.

Using excessive force is abusive and unlawful, but the danger lies in the term “Minimum Force”. Unintentionally, we can enter a situation known as “[[Unintended consequences|The law of unintended consequence]]”.

Positive Handling is a statutory and mandatory training, in accordance to Section 2 and 3 of the [[Health and Safety at Work etc. Act 1974|Health and Safety as Work Act 1974]].

It represents a significant investment and undertaking for all staff. Increasingly, staff and managers have expressed the need to acknowledge existing understanding and experience due to raising violence in schools.

